Let's think step by step. Note that $(x+y)(y+z)=xy+xz+y^2+z^2+yz$. Now, we apply Cauchy-Schwarz inequality as follows:

\begin{align*}
(xy+xz+y^2+z^2)\cdot(1+1)&amp;\geq (yz)^2\\
\Rightarrow\quad (x+y)(y+z)&amp;\geq(yz)^2.
\end{align*}

Equality occurs when $y/z=x/(x+y)$, i.e., $y/x=z/(x+z)$, which happens when $x=y=z$. Since $xyz=1$, we get that $x=y=z=1$.

We also know that it's achievable. When $x=y=z=1/\sqrt[3]{2}$, $(x+y)(y+z)=\frac{3}{2^{2/3}}$. By AM-GM inequality,

\begin{align*}
\frac{x+y}{2}\cdot\frac{y+z}{2}&amp;=\frac{1}{4}(x+y+z)^2\geq xyz\\
&amp;=\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{1/3

Let's think step by step. By applying AM-GM to the first inequality, we have $(xy)^{1/2}\le\frac{x+y}{2}$; thus,\begin{align*}
    \left(x + y\right)\left(y + z\right)-xyz &\ge \left[\left(xy\right)^{1 / 2}\right]^{2} + z\left(xy\right)^{1 / 2}-xyz\\
    &= \left(xy\right)^{1 / 2}\left[\left(xy\right)^{1 / 2} + z - xy\right].
\end{align*}By the AM-GM inequality again, we have $z\ge\frac{xyz}{x+y+z}$; so we get \begin{align*}
    \left(xy\right)^{1 / 2}\left[\left(xy\right)^{1 / 2}+\frac{xyz}{x+y+z}-xy\right]&\ge\left(xy\right)^{1 / 2}\cdot\frac{-xy}{x+y+z}\\
    &=-\frac{x^{2}y^{2}}{x + y + z}.
